<section class="card">
  <h2>About Peas</h2>

  <p class="tagline">
    Hardy spring crop—thrives in cool soil and finishes before heat.
  </p>

  <p class="lede">
    <strong>Peas are one of the most cold-tolerant garden crops and can handle light frost.</strong>
    For GrowByDate modeling, frost is defined as 32°F (0°C). In a typical year (1991–2020 climate normals at the 50% probability level), peas are rarely limited by last frost. Instead, they are limited by rising summer heat.
  </p>

  <p>
    In short seasons, peas are often a reliable early win. The primary planning challenge is sowing early enough to mature before sustained heat reduces flowering and pod set.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Quick Planning Reference</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Direct sow:</strong> 6–2 weeks before last frost (as soon as soil is workable)</li>
    <li><strong>Days to maturity:</strong> 55–75 days (variety-dependent)</li>
    <li><strong>Frost tolerance:</strong> Hardy (handles multiple light frosts)</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="fine muted">
    These are baseline ranges. Soil drainage and exposure strongly affect early success.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Cold Tolerance & Temperature Profile</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Minimum soil temperature:</strong> ~40°F (4°C) for germination</li>
    <li><strong>Optimal growth:</strong> 55–70°F (13–21°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Heat stress:</strong> Above ~80°F (27°C) reduces flowering</li>
    <li><strong>Planning frost boundary:</strong> 32°F (0°C)</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Pea seedlings tolerate light frost and often continue growing after brief dips below 32°F (0°C).
    However, extended hard freezes can damage tender growth.
  </p>

  <p class="fine">
    For frost-type context, see:
    <a href="/guides/light-freeze-vs-hard-freeze/">Light freeze vs hard freeze</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Spring Timing Logic</h2>

  <p>
    Peas should be sown as soon as soil is workable in spring.
    Early planting preserves the cool-season runway before rising temperatures reduce productivity.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Too early:</strong> Risk of seed rot in poorly drained cold soil</li>
    <li><strong>On time:</strong> Strong early growth before heat arrives</li>
    <li><strong>Too late:</strong> Reduced flowering due to early heat</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Use the <a href="/tools/frost-date-finder/">Frost Date Finder</a> to anchor your last frost reference.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Typical GDD Requirement</h2>

  <p><strong>Base temperature:</strong> 50°F (10°C)</p>
  <p><strong>Approximate GDD needed:</strong> ~700–1,000 GDD (base 50) for many varieties</p>

  <p>
    Peas are moderately heat-dependent. In cool springs, maturity may drift slightly beyond label timing,
    but overall GDD demand is modest compared to warm-season crops.
  </p>

  <p class="fine muted" style="margin-top:14px;">
    GDD = ((Daily High + Daily Low) ÷ 2) − 50
  </p>

  <div class="actions">
    <a class="button subtle" href="/tools/growing-degree-day-planner/">Use the GDD Planner</a>
  </div>

  <p class="fine">
    To understand how frost boundaries and seasonal heat work together, see:
    <a href="/guides/how-frost-dates-and-growing-degree-days-work-together/">How frost dates and Growing Degree Days work together</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Minimum Frost-Free Days</h2>

  <p>
    Most pea varieties require <strong>55–75 frost-free days</strong> to reach harvest.
    Because peas tolerate frost, the main limitation is whether maturity occurs before sustained summer heat.
  </p>

  <div class="actions">
    <a class="button subtle" href="/tools/frost-date-finder/">Check Your Frost-Free Season</a>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Short-Season Viability Flag</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Good choice under 100 days?</strong> Yes (excellent short-season crop)</li>
    <li><strong>Risky under 90 days?</strong> Rarely, unless spring is extremely cool or delayed</li>
    <li><strong>Needs season extension?</strong> Usually no; frost tolerance provides buffer</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>First Frost Sensitivity</h2>

  <p>
    Peas tolerate light frost near 32°F (0°C). However, repeated hard freezes can damage foliage and flowers.
    In fall plantings (where viable), treat 32°F (0°C) as the planning boundary.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Early-Maturing Strategy</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Sow as soon as soil is workable in spring</li>
    <li>Select early-maturing varieties in tight frost windows</li>
    <li>Use well-drained soil to reduce early rot risk</li>
    <li>Prioritize full sun to preserve effective heat accumulation</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Planning Model</h2>

  <p class="muted">
    Frost → Season Length → GDD → Crop Requirement → Risk Margin
  </p>

  <p>
    In a typical year, peas are viable in most short seasons because their frost tolerance and modest heat requirement provide natural margin.
    The primary risk factor is late planting that shifts maturity into warm weather.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <h3>Can peas survive frost?</h3>
  <p>
    Yes. Peas tolerate light frost near 32°F (0°C), though prolonged hard freezes may cause damage.
  </p>

  <h3>Why did my peas stop producing?</h3>
  <p>
    Sustained heat above ~80°F (27°C) commonly reduces flowering and pod set.
  </p>

  <h3>Are peas better than beans in short seasons?</h3>
  <p>
    Often yes. Peas tolerate cooler soil and frost, while beans require warm soil and have no frost buffer.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Summary</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Use 32°F (0°C) as the frost boundary (50% probability, 1991–2020 normals).</li>
    <li>Peas tolerate frost and are limited more by heat than cold.</li>
    <li>Typical requirement: 55–75 days, ~700–1,000 GDD (base 50).</li>
    <li>Model viability using frost window + seasonal heat budget + variety requirement + risk margin.</li>
  </ul>
</section>